data.title: As Janet Jackson confirms that she is pregnant at 49 FEMAIL spotlights others
data.meta_description: Janet turns 50 on May 16 and is expecting her first child with husband Wissam Al Mana. Laura Linney, Geena Davis, Kelly Preston, Halle Berry, and Holy Hunter all gave birth in their late 40s.
data.text:
News that Janet Jackson is pregnant for the first time at 49 years old — she turns 50 on May 16 — has already grabbed plenty of headlines this week.

'I thought it was important that you be the first to know. My husband and I are planning our family. So I’m going to have to delay the tour,' she told social media followers, adding: 'I have to rest up, doctor’s orders.'

But while the pop icon is certainly getting on in years to be starting a family with husband Wissam Al Mana, 41, she's hardly the first celebrity to share the shocking news that she's expecting well into her 40s.

Here, FEMAIL rounded up a long list of moms who chose to start motherhood — or expand their families — after age 44, with some moms welcoming little ones into their 50s.

Scroll down for video

Laura Linney: 49

Now 52, in 2014 the Truman Show star gave birth to her only son, Bennett Armistead Schauer, at age 49 — just a month shy of turning 50.

She and her husband, real estate agent Wissam al Mana, had kept mum about the pregnancy, and the news that she had given birth was a big surprise to the public.

Laura did notably take some time off from being in the public eye before their child was born, though, attending her last red carpet event about seven months before Bennett arrived.

Geena Davis: 48

Geena, 60, has never confirmed that she used IVF to get pregnant with her three children, all of whom she had in her 40s — though people certainly speculated that she had.

The mother-of-three gave birth to fraternal twin sons Kian William and Kaiis Steven in 2004 at the age of 48 with her 15-years-younger fourth husband, Reza Jarrahy.

Before that, the couple had welcomed their first child, a daughter named Alizeh Keshvar, in 2002, when Geena was 46.

'She never had one problem during her pregnancy, not one bit of morning sickness,' her dad, William Davis, told People. 'And Geena said the birth was no big deal. She was in labor something like 4½ hours. For a first-time birth, and at her age, it's amazing. She's amazing."

Kelly Preston: 48

Hearts broke for Kelly Preston, 48, and her husband John Travolta when their teenage son Jett died tragically and unexpectedly in 2009.

But the public grief for the famous couple turned to confusion when, just months later, they announced they were expecting another child — a boy named Benjamin, whom Kelly gave birth to in 2010 at the age of 48.

'We had been trying for quite a few years, and then of course there was a time when we weren’t, and then we started trying again,' she told Health magazine. 'When I found out I was pregnant, I was floored. I’d snuck out of bed and then came back and woke Johnny up in bed. We both started crying. It was wonderful.

'It’s pretty amazing having a child at this age,' she went on.

The pregnancy, though, was plagued by rumors. Some speculated that the timing, especially given Kelly's age, was too convenient, and talk persisted that she was 'faking' it with a faux belly while expecting a child via surrogate.

Halle Berry: 47

Now 49, Halle was 47 when she welcomed her second child: a son, Maceo, with then-husband Olivier Martinez.

'They call it a geriatric pregnancy,' she told Ellen DeGeneres in 2014, adding: 'I was, you know, on my way…this is probably way TMI, but I was really, you know, kinda premenopausal so to have this happen was a huge [shock].'

Halle was already 41 when she gave birth to her daughter Nahla, now eight, with then-husband Gabriel Aubry.

Holly Hunter: 47

The Oscar winner, who is now 58, was 47 when she welcomed her twin boys, Claude and Press, in January 2006 with British actor Gordon MacDonald.

'I kind of don’t talk about them in public,’ she told talk show host Craig Furguson when he asked about their ages. When pressed on whether she did, in fact, have children, she went on: 'I can’t deny or confirm…’

Marcia Cross: 45

Marcia, 54, has been perfectly up-front about using IVF to conceive her fraternal twin daughters, Eden and Savannah, who were born in February 2007 when she was a month away from turning 45.

'We did in vitro a week after we got married,' she told People of her plan with husband Tom Mahoney. 'We were supposed to go to Greece and Paris and have this fancy honeymoon, and I said, "Let's stay put and see if we can't give this baby a chance."'

The Desperate Housewives star welcomed the little girls via C-section a month early, after being diagnosed with preeclempsia.

Iman: 45

Iman was nearly 22 when she gave birth to her first daughter, Zulekah, in 1978 — but she was 45 when she and David Bowie welcomed Alexandria Zahra Jones in 2000.

'I did IVF, but nothing happened. So I began to think of adoption and then I got pregnant. It was definitely a miracle,' the supermodel told Parade.

Now 60, Iman is still raising a teenager long after her 37-year-old daughter left the nest.

Susan Sarandon: 45

The 69-year-old Oscar winner has three children, with her youngest, Miles Guthrie, coming into the world in May 1992 — when Susan was 45.

But it was the fact that she was able to have children at all, never mind her age, that was the real surprise for the star. After being diagnosed with endometriosis, she'd been told she'd never had kids — and managed to go a long time without conceiving, even while off birth control.

Miles was her second son with ex-husband Tim Robbins. Her first, Jack Henry, was born when Susan was 42. She also had a daughter, Eva Amurri, when she was 38.

Rachel Dratch: 44

Rachel Dratch was just as surprised as everyone else when she found herself pregnant at 43. According to her boyfriend, John Wahl, she'd written off being able to have a family.

'I had bought into all this stuff about, "Once you're over 40..."' she told People. 'I'd gone through the whole process of letting go of [the idea of having kids].'

But in 2010 at the age of 44, the now-50-year-old comedian welcomed son Eli Benjamin into the world.

Jane Seymour: 44

At 44, the Dr. Quinn, Medicine Woman star defied medical odds when she and her then-husband James Keach had twins in 1995.

Now 65, Jane revealed she'd had two miscarriages before conceiving John Stacy and Kristopher Steven via IVF.

The little ones were named for singer Johnny Cash and Superman Christopher Reeve.

Marcia Gay Harden: 44

Marcia already had a four-year-old daughter when she welcomed twins with then-husband Thaddaeus Scheel at the age of 44.

Julitta Dee Scheel and Hudson Scheel Harden were born in 2004, and Marica was especially excited to have a boy.

'I’d wanted to be pregnant for a long time,' she told Entertainment Weekly.

Gwen Stefani: 44

The Make Me Like You singer, 46, was 44 when she had her third son, Apollo Bowie Flynn.

And he wasn't expected, either. In fact, Gwen had told her oldest son, Kingston, that their family was all set the way it was — but a visit form now ex-husband Gavin Rossdale while he was touring changing all that.

'I wasn’t home often but I got home on Father's Day and that gave Father's Day a new meaning,' he told Howard Stern.

Elizabeth Edwards: 51

Nobody seemed to care about his age when, at almost 54, Elizabeth's husband John Edwards fathered a child with his mistress, Rielle Hunter — but then again, there were more interesting things to talk about.

Yet Elizabeth was considerably far along in life when she gave birth to the couple's youngest child, Jack, in 2000.

The lawyer and best-selling author died after a long battle with breast cancer in 2010.

Annie Leibovitz: 52

At 51, the famed photographer became a mom when she gave birth to a daughter, Sarah, using donated sperm.

The now-66-year-old and writer and filmmaker Susan Sontag had been involved for years, but Susan, according to New York Magazine, wasn't behind the idea of Annie having a baby.

In 2004, after Susan passed away from cancer, Annie used a surrogate to have two more children: Twins she named Susan (after her long-term partner) and Samuelle (after her own father, Sam).

Cheryl Tiegs: 52

Not all late-in-life moms conceive and carry their little ones, though. Cheryl was 52 and on her fourth marriage to now ex-husband Rod Stryker when the two welcomed twins via surrogacy.

The 68-year-old supermodel's kids, Theo and Jaden, arrived in 2000.

'I can't say that all women should become mothers after 50,' she told People when they were still newborns. 'Yet for me, it's great. It was the right decision.'

Joan Lunden: 53

Joan Lunden, 65, also welcomed twins via surrogacy — two pairs, in fact, in addition to children she had from a previous marriage.

Both sets of babies were welcomed with husband Jeff Konigsberg. The youngest, fraternal twins named Kimberly Elise and Jack Andrew, were born in 2005 when Joan was 53.

'We tried in vitro fertilization many times, but it wasn't working,' she told MSNBC's Deborah Norville. 'But when you're approaching 50, it's also a time game and you have to ask yourself, "Is it really about me being pregnant, or is it about parenting and having babies?" So we decided to use a surrogate.'

Lucy Liu: 46

The single Charlie's Angels star, 47, used a surrogate and donated sperm to have her son, Rockwell Lloyd, last year.

'I never feel like it’s too early or too late for anything,' she told USA Today. 'I don't ever think for me this traditional way is the way to go for me because I haven't had a traditional life.'
